    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d9cb6394-afed-403d-afd4-73942a2fdfe6",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 50-year-old man who appears mildly uncomfortable when moving from sitting to standing, often bracing one hand against the armrest or his thigh before straightening fully. He is overweight with a stocky build and shows guarded posture with slightly reduced lumbar range of motion. He reports a dull, aching pain across the lower back with intermittent sharp twinges after bending, prolonged driving, or lifting objects. He denies bowel or bladder dysfunction and has no saddle anesthesia, but notes morning stiffness and worsening discomfort late in the workday.\n\nHe works full-time as a warehouse supervisor, a role that mixes desk work with intermittent lifting, climbing stairs, and long periods on concrete floors. Outside work, {patientName} enjoys weekend fishing, watching his son’s recreational baseball games, and doing light home improvement projects, though he has recently cut back because of back pain. He is married, lives with his spouse, and has a supportive family network, but says the pain has made him more irritable and less active socially over the past few months.\n\nHis daily routine is largely sedentary outside of work demands. He drives about 45 minutes each way to work, sleeps on his side, and says sleep quality has worsened because turning in bed can trigger discomfort. He does not smoke, drinks alcohol socially on weekends, and has an inconsistent exercise pattern. He has tried over-the-counter heat wraps and occasional stretching videos online, with only partial relief.\n\nOn examination, he would likely appear afebrile and hemodynamically stable, with localized tenderness over the paraspinal lumbar muscles and no obvious deformity. His gait is slightly stiff but independent. He is concerned that the pain may interfere with his job security, although he remains motivated to stay working and avoid opioid medication if possible."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9a503f6b-171e-4647-b08b-f597da236720",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has had intermittent episodes of low back discomfort over the past 3 years, usually after strenuous activity or long work shifts, but this current flare has persisted for about 6 weeks. He describes pain intensity ranging from 3/10 at rest to 7/10 after lifting or prolonged standing. He has not had prior spine surgery and has never been hospitalized for back pain. He denies recent falls, motor vehicle accidents, fever, chills, night sweats, unexplained weight loss, lower-extremity numbness, progressive weakness, or changes in bowel or bladder function.\n\nHis past medical history is notable for essential hypertension and seasonal allergic rhinitis. He has no known inflammatory arthritis, malignancy, chronic infection, or osteoporosis. He is not taking anticoagulants and has no history of chronic corticosteroid use. He uses occasional ibuprofen with food and says it helps somewhat. His work involves variable physical strain, including lifting boxes and frequent bending, and he admits he has not maintained regular core-strengthening exercise.\n\n{patientName} has never smoked cigarettes and denies illicit drug use. He drinks 1-2 beers on some weekends. Diet is mixed, with frequent takeout meals during workdays, and his weight has gradually increased over the past decade. He lives with his wife and remains independent in all activities of daily living, though he avoids yard work and heavy chores during pain flares."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
